Finding patterns using Association Rules

Association rule is a rule-based machine learning method for discovering interesting relations between variables in large databases.

library(tidyverse)
library(arules)

Preparing data

Merging transactions and products’ names;
Saving as .csv to read later using read.transactions()

data.prod <- data %>%
    inner_join(products, by = "PRODUCT_ID") %>%
    select(BASKET_ID, SUB_COMMODITY_DESC) %>%
    write_csv(tosave.path)


Converting dataframe to sparse matrix:

transactions <- read.transactions(tosave.path
                                ,format = "single"  # the format of the dataframe is long, not wide
                                ,sep = ","
                                ,cols = c("BASKET_ID", "SUB_COMMODITY_DESC"))


Now we have the data ready to be used for market basket analysis

Basic concepts

  • Support

  • measures how frequently it occurs in the data \[{support(X)} = {{count(X)} \over {N}}\]

  • Confidence

  • measures the predictive power or accuracy \[{confidence(X->Y)} = {{support(X,Y)} \over {support(X)}}\]

  • Lift

  • measures how much likely one item is to be purchased relative to its typical purchase rate, given that you know another item has been purchased. \[{lift(X->Y)} = {{confidence(X,Y)} \over {support(Y)}}\]

Creating the model

transactions.rules <- apriori(transactions
    ,parameter = list(support = 0.003  # minimum support
    ,confidence = 0.25  # minimum confidence
    ,minlen = 2))  # minimum number of items per rule

Improving model

Removing products that are purchased too often

nomilk.rules <- subset(transactions.rules, !items %in% c("FLUID MILK WHITE ONLY", "BANANAS", "MAINSTREAM", "SHREDDED CHEESE"))


Interesting findings:

  • Those who buy Preservers jam marmalade are 11.7 times more likely to also buy Peanut butter
  • Those who buy Bagels are 10.6 times more likely to also buy Cream cheese
  • Those who buy Skillet dinners are 9.3 times more likely to also buy Tuna
  • Those who buy Fruit snacks are 6.03 times more likely to also buy Kids cereal
  • Those who buy Hamburger buns and Soft drinks can are 4.8 times more likely to also buy Potato chips
